[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] The **Canvas API** provides a means for drawing graphics via JavaScript and the HTML `<canvas>` element.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] Among other things, it can be used for animation, game graphics, data visualization, photo manipulation, and real-time video processing.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] The Canvas API largely focuses on 2D graphics.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] The WebGL API, which also uses the `<canvas>` element, draws hardware-accelerated 2D and 3D graphics.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] This simple example draws a green rectangle onto a canvas.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] The `Document.getElementById()` method gets a reference to the HTML `<canvas>` element.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] Next, the `HTMLCanvasElement.getContext()` method gets that element's context—the thing onto which the drawing will be rendered.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] The actual drawing is done using the `CanvasRenderingContext2D` interface.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] The `fillStyle` property makes the rectangle green.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] The `fillRect()` method places its top-left corner at (10, 10), and gives it a size of 150 units wide by 100 tall.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] `CanvasCaptureMediaStreamTrack` is a related interface.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] A comprehensive tutorial covering both the basic usage of the Canvas API and its advanced features.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] A hands-on, book-length introduction to the Canvas API and WebGL.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] Combining `<video>` and `<canvas>` to manipulate video data in real time.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] The Canvas API is extremely powerful, but not always simple to use.
[src:chartjs/api-canvas-api] The libraries listed below can make the creation of canvas-based projects faster and easier.
[src:chartjs/canvas-api-tutorial] This tutorial describes how to use the **`<canvas>`** element to draw 2D graphics, starting with the basics.
[src:chartjs/canvas-api-tutorial] The examples provided should give you some clear ideas about what you can do with canvas, and will provide code snippets that may get you started in building your own content.
[src:chartjs/canvas-api-tutorial] `<canvas>` is an HTML element which can be used to draw graphics via scripting (usually JavaScript).
[src:chartjs/canvas-api-tutorial] This can, for instance, be used to draw graphs, combine photos, or create simple animations.
[src:chartjs/canvas-api-tutorial] First introduced in WebKit by Apple for the macOS Dashboard, `<canvas>` has since been implemented in browsers.
[src:chartjs/canvas-api-tutorial] Using the `<canvas>` element is not very difficult, but you do need a basic understanding of HTML and JavaScript.
[src:chartjs/canvas-api-tutorial] The `<canvas>` element is not supported in some older browsers, but is supported in recent versions of all major browsers.
[src:chartjs/canvas-api-tutorial] The default size of the canvas is 300 pixels × 150 pixels (width × height).
[src:chartjs/canvas-api-tutorial] But custom sizes can be defined using the HTML `height` and `width` property.
[src:chartjs/canvas-api-tutorial] In order to draw graphics on the canvas we use a JavaScript context object, which creates graphics on the fly.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The **`CanvasRenderingContext2D`** interface, part of the Canvas API, provides the 2D rendering context for the drawing surface of a `<canvas>` element.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] It is used for drawing shapes, text, images, and other objects.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The interface's properties and methods are described in the reference section of this page.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The Canvas tutorial has more explanation, examples, and resources, as well.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] For `OffscreenCanvas`, there is an equivalent interface that provides the rendering context.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The offscreen rendering context inherits most of the same properties and methods as the `CanvasRenderingContext2D` and is described in more detail in the `OffscreenCanvasRenderingContext2D` reference page.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] With the context in hand, you can draw anything you like.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Returns an object containing the context attributes used by the browser.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Context attributes can be requested when using `HTMLCanvasElement.getContext()` to create the 2D context.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Returns `true` if the rendering context was lost.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] There are three methods that immediately draw rectangles to the canvas.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Sets all pixels in the rectangle defined by starting point *(x, y)* and size *(width, height)* to transparent black, erasing any previously drawn content.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Draws a filled rectangle at *(x, y)* position whose size is determined by *width* and *height*.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Paints a rectangle which has a starting point at *(x, y)* and has a *w* width and an *h* height onto the canvas, using the current stroke style.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] See also the `TextMetrics` object for text properties.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Draws (fills) a given text at the given (x, y) position.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Draws (strokes) a given text at the given (x, y) position.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The following methods and properties control how lines are drawn.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `butt` (default), `round`, `square`.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Defines the type of corners where two lines meet.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `round`, `bevel`, `miter` (default).
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Returns the current line dash pattern array containing an even number of non-negative numbers.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Specifies where to start a dash array on a line.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The following properties control how text is laid out.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `start` (default), `end`, `left`, `right`, `center`.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `top`, `hanging`, `middle`, `alphabetic` (default), `ideographic`, `bottom`.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `ltr`, `rtl`, `inherit` (default).
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `auto` (default), `normal`, `none`.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `ultra-condensed`, `extra-condensed`, `condensed`, `semi-condensed`, `normal` (default), `semi-expanded`, `expanded`, `extra-expanded`, `ultra-expanded`.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `normal` (default), `small-caps`, `all-small-caps`, `petite-caps`, `all-petite-caps`, `unicase`, `titling-caps`.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Possible values: `auto` (default), `optimizeSpeed`, `optimizeLegibility`, `geometricPrecision`.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Gets or sets the language of the canvas drawing context.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Fill styling is used for colors and styles inside shapes and stroke styling is used for the lines around shapes.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Color or style to use for the lines around shapes.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a conic gradient around a point given by coordinates represented by the parameters.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a linear gradient along the line given by the coordinates represented by the parameters.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a radial gradient given by the coordinates of the two circles represented by the parameters.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a pattern using the specified image.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] It repeats the source in the directions specified by the repetition argument.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Horizontal distance the shadow will be offset.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Vertical distance the shadow will be offset.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The following methods can be used to manipulate paths of objects.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Starts a new path by emptying the list of sub-paths.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Call this method when you want to create a new path.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Causes the point of the pen to move back to the start of the current sub-path.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] It tries to draw a straight line from the current point to the start.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] If the shape has already been closed or has only one point, this function does nothing.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Moves the starting point of a new sub-path to the (x, y) coordinates.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Connects the last point in the current sub-path to the specified (x, y) coordinates with a straight line.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a cubic Bézier curve to the current path.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a quadratic Bézier curve to the current path.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a circular arc to the current path.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds an arc to the current path with the given control points and radius, connected to the previous point by a straight line.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds an elliptical arc to the current path.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a path for a rectangle at position (x, y) with a size that is determined by *width* and *height*.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a path for a rounded rectangle with a specified position, width, height, and corner radii.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Fills the current sub-paths with the current fill style.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Strokes the current sub-paths with the current stroke style.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] If a given element is focused, this method draws a focus ring around the current path.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a clipping path from the current sub-paths.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Everything drawn after `clip()` is called appears inside the clipping path only.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] For an example, see Clipping paths in the Canvas tutorial.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Reports whether or not the specified point is contained in the current path.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Reports whether or not the specified point is inside the area contained by the stroking of a path.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Objects in the `CanvasRenderingContext2D` rendering context have a current transformation matrix and methods to manipulate it.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The transformation matrix is applied when creating the current default path, painting text, shapes and `Path2D` objects.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The methods listed below remain for historical and compatibility reasons as `DOMMatrix` objects are used in most parts of the API nowadays and will be used in the future instead.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Retrieves the current transformation matrix being applied to the context.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a rotation to the transformation matrix.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The angle argument represents a clockwise rotation angle and is expressed in radians.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a scaling transformation to the canvas units by x horizontally and by y vertically.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Adds a translation transformation by moving the canvas and its origin x horizontally and y vertically on the grid.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Multiplies the current transformation matrix with the matrix described by its arguments.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Resets the current transform to the identity matrix, and then invokes the `transform()` method with the same arguments.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Resets the current transform by the identity matrix.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Alpha value that is applied to shapes and images before they are composited onto the canvas.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] With `globalAlpha` applied this sets how shapes and images are drawn onto the existing bitmap.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] This method is available in multiple formats, providing a great deal of flexibility in its use.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Creates a new, blank `ImageData` object with the specified dimensions.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] All of the pixels in the new object are transparent black.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Returns an `ImageData` object representing the underlying pixel data for the area of the canvas denoted by the rectangle which starts at *(sx, sy)* and has an *sw* width and *sh* height.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Paints data from the given `ImageData` object onto the bitmap.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] If a dirty rectangle is provided, only the pixels from that rectangle are painted.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Image smoothing mode; if disabled, images will not be smoothed if scaled.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Allows you to set the quality of image smoothing.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] The `CanvasRenderingContext2D` rendering context contains a variety of drawing style states (attributes for line styles, fill styles, shadow styles, text styles).
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Saves the current drawing style state using a stack so you can revert any change you make to it using `restore()`.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Restores the drawing style state to the last element on the 'state stack' saved by `save()`.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] A read-only back-reference to the `HTMLCanvasElement`.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Might be `null` if it is not associated with a `<canvas>` element.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Resets the rendering context, including the backing buffer, the drawing state stack, path, and styles.
[src:chartjs/canvasrenderingcontext2d] Applies a CSS or SVG filter to the canvas, e.g., to change its brightness or blurriness.
[src:chartjs/chart-js] Chart.js has had four major version releases as detailed below.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:chartjs/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Infographics have been around for many years and recently the increase of the number of easy-to-use, free tools have made the creation of infographics available to a large segment of the population.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Social media sites such as Facebook and Twitter have also allowed for individual infographics to be spread among many people around the world.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Infographics are widely used in the age of short attention span.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In newspapers, infographics are commonly used to show the weather, as well as maps, site plans, and graphs for summaries of data.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Some books are almost entirely made up of information graphics, such as David Macaulay's *The Way Things Work*.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The Snapshots in *USA Today* are also an example of simple infographics used to convey news and current events.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Modern maps, especially route maps for transit systems, use infographic techniques to integrate a variety of information, such as the conceptual layout of the transit network, transfer points, and local landmarks.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Public transportation maps, such as those for the Washington Metro and the London Underground map, are well-known infographics.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Public places such as transit terminals usually have some sort of integrated "signage system" with standardized icons and stylized maps.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In 1626, Christoph Scheiner published the *Rosa Ursina sive Sol*, a book that revealed his research about the rotation of the sun.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Infographics appeared in the form of illustrations demonstrating the Sun's rotation patterns.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In 1786, William Playfair, an engineer and political economist, published the first data graphs in his book *The Commercial and Political Atlas*.
[src:chartjs/infographic] To represent the economy of 18th century England, Playfair used statistical graphs, bar charts, line graphs, area charts, and histograms.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In his work, *Statistical Breviary*, he is credited with introducing the first pie chart.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Around 1820, modern geography was established by Carl Ritter.
[src:chartjs/infographic] His maps included shared frames, agreed map legends, scales, repeatability, and fidelity.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Such a map can be considered a "supersign" which combines sign systems—as defined by Charles Sanders Peirce—consisting of symbols, icons, indexes as representations.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Other examples can be seen in the works of geographers Ritter and Alexander von Humboldt.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In 1857, English nurse Florence Nightingale used information graphics to persuade Queen Victoria to improve conditions in military hospitals.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The principal one she used was the Coxcomb chart, a combination of stacked bar and pie charts, depicting the number and causes of deaths during each month of the Crimean War.
[src:chartjs/infographic] 1861 saw the release of an influential information graphic on the subject of Napoleon's disastrous march on Moscow.
[src:chartjs/infographic] James Joseph Sylvester introduced the term "graph" in 1878 in the scientific magazine *Nature* and published a set of diagrams showing the relationship between chemical bonds and mathematical properties.
[src:chartjs/infographic] These were also some of the first mathematical graphs.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In 1900, the African-American historian, sociologist, writer, and Black rights activist, W.E.B.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Du Bois presented data visualizations at the Exposition Universelle (1900) in Paris, France.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In addition to curating 500 photographs of the lives of Black Americans, Du Bois and his Atlanta University team of students and scholars created 60 handmade data visualizations to document the ways Black Americans were being denied access to education, housing, employment, and household wealth.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The Cologne Progressives developed an aesthetic approach to art that focused on communicating information.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Gerd Arntz, Peter Alma and Augustin Tschinkel, all participants in this movement were recruited by Otto Neurath for the Gesellschafts- und Wirtschaftsmuseum, where they developed the Vienna Method from 1926 to 1934.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Here simple images were used to represent data in a structured way.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Following the victory of Austrofascism in the Austrian Civil War, the team moved to the Netherlands where they continued their work rebranding it Isotypes (International System of Typographic Picture Education).
[src:chartjs/infographic] The method was also applied by IZOSTAT (ИЗОСТАТ) in the Soviet Union.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In 1942 Isidore Isou published the Lettrist manifesto, a document covering art, culture, poetry, film, and political theory.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The included works also called metagraphics and hypergraphics, are a synthesis of writing and visual art.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In 1958 Stephen Toulmin proposed a graphical argument model, called The Toulmin Model of Argumentation.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The diagram contained six interrelated components used for analyzing arguments and was considered Toulmin's most influential work, particularly in the field of rhetoric, communication, and computer science.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The Toulmin Model of Argumentation became influential in argumentation theory and its applications.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In 1972 and 1973, respectively, the Pioneer 10 and Pioneer 11 spacecraft included on their vessels the Pioneer Plaques, a pair of gold-anodized aluminum plaques, each featuring a pictorial message.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The pictorial messages included nude male and female figures as well as symbols that were intended to provide information about the origin of the spacecraft.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The images were designed by Carl Sagan and Frank Drake and were unique in that their graphical meanings were to be understandable to extraterrestrial beings, who would have no conception of human language.
[src:chartjs/infographic] A pioneer in data visualization, Edward Tufte, wrote a series of books – *Visual Explanations*, *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, and *Envisioning Information* – on the subject of information graphics.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Referred to by The New York Times as the "da Vinci of Data", Tufte began to give day-long lectures and workshops on the subject of infographics starting in 1993.
[src:chartjs/infographic] As of 2012, Tufte still gives these lectures.
[src:chartjs/infographic] To Tufte, good data visualizations represent every data point accurately and enable a viewer to see trends and patterns in the data.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Tufte's contribution to the field of data visualization and infographics is considered immense, and his design principles can be seen in many websites, magazines, and newspapers today.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The infographics created by Peter Sullivan for The Sunday Times in the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s were some of the key factors in encouraging newspapers to use more infographics.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Sullivan is also one of the few authors who have written about information graphics in newspapers.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Likewise, the staff artists at USA Today, the United States newspaper that debuted in 1982, established the goal of using graphics to make information easier to comprehend.
[src:chartjs/infographic] However, the paper has received criticism for oversimplifying news stories and for creating infographics that some find emphasizes entertainment over content and data.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Tufte coined the term chartjunk to refer to graphics that are visually appealing to the point of losing the information contained within them.
[src:chartjs/infographic] With vector graphics and raster graphics becoming ubiquitous in computing in the 21st century, data visualizations have been applied to commonly used computer systems, including desktop publishing and Geographic Information Systems (GIS).
[src:chartjs/infographic] Closely related to the field of information graphics is information design, which is the creation of infographics.
[src:chartjs/infographic] By the year 2000, Adobe Flash-based animations on the Internet had made use of many key practices in creating infographics in order to create a variety of products and games.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Likewise, television began to incorporate infographics into the viewers' experiences in the early 2000s.
[src:chartjs/infographic] One example of infographics usage in television and in pop culture is the 2002 music video by the Norwegian musicians of Röyksopp, for their song "Remind Me." The video was composed entirely of animated infographics.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Similarly, in 2004, a television commercial for the French nuclear technology company Areva used animated infographics as an advertising tactic.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Both of these videos and the attention they received have conveyed to other fields the potential value of using information graphics to describe complex information efficiently.
[src:chartjs/infographic] With the rise of alternatives to Adobe Flash, such as HTML 5 and CSS3, infographics are now created in a variety of media with a number of software tools.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The field of journalism has also incorporated and applied information graphics to news stories.
[src:chartjs/infographic] For stories that intend to include text, images, and graphics, the system called the maestro concept allows entire newsrooms to collaborate and organize a story to successfully incorporate all components.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Across many newsrooms, this teamwork-integrated system is applied to improve time management.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The maestro system is designed to improve the presentation of stories for busy readers of media.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Many news-based websites have also used interactive information graphics in which the user can extract information on a subject as they explore the graphic.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Many businesses use infographics as a medium for communicating with and attracting potential customers.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Information graphics are a form of content marketing and have become a tool for internet marketers and companies to create content that others will link to, thus possibly boosting a company's reputation and online presence.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Religious denominations have also started using infographics.
[src:chartjs/infographic] For example, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has made numerous infographics to help people learn about their faith, missionaries, temples, lay ministry, and family history efforts.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Infographics are finding a home in the classroom as well.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Courses that teach students to create their own infographics using a variety of tools may encourage engagement in the classroom and may lead to a better understanding of the concepts they are mapping onto the graphics.
[src:chartjs/infographic] With the popularity of social media, infographics have become popular, often as static images or simple web interfaces, covering any number of topics.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Such infographics are often shared between users of social networks such as Facebook, Twitter, Pinterest, Google+ and Reddit.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The hashtag #infographic was tweeted 56,765 times in March 2012 and at its peak 3,365 times in a span of 24 hours.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The three parts of all infographics are the visual, the content, and the knowledge.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The visual consists of colors and graphics.
[src:chartjs/infographic] There are two different types of graphics – theme, and reference.
[src:chartjs/infographic] These graphics are included in all infographics and represent the underlying visual representation of the data.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Reference graphics are generally icons that can be used to point to certain data, although they are not always found in infographics.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Statistics and facts usually serve as the content for infographics and can be obtained from any number of sources, including census data and news reports.
[src:chartjs/infographic] One of the most important aspects of infographics is that they contain some sort of insight into the data that they are presenting – this is the knowledge.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Infographics are effective because of their visual element.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Humans receive input from all five of their senses (sight, touch, hearing, smell, taste), but they receive significantly more information from vision than any of the other four.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Fifty percent of the human brain is dedicated to visual functions, and images are processed faster than text.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The brain processes pictures all at once, but processes text in a linear fashion, meaning it takes much longer to obtain information from text.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Entire business processes or industry sectors can be made relevant to a new audience through a guidance design technique that leads the eye.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The page may link to a complete report, but the infographic primes the reader making the subject-matter more accessible.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Online trends, such as the increasingly short attention span of Internet users, has also contributed to the increasing popularity and effectiveness of infographics.
[src:chartjs/infographic] When designing the visual aspect of an infographic, a number of considerations must be made to optimize the effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The six components of visual encoding are spatial, marks, connection, enclosure, retinal properties, and temporal encoding.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Each of these can be utilized in its own way to represent relationships between different types of data.
[src:chartjs/infographic] However, studies have shown that spatial position is the most effective way to represent numerical data and leads to the fastest and easiest understanding by viewers.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Therefore, the designers often spatially represent the most important relationship being depicted in an infographic.
[src:chartjs/infographic] There are also three basic provisions of communication that need to be assessed when designing an infographic – appeal, comprehension, and retention.
[src:chartjs/infographic] "Appeal" is the idea that communication needs to engage its audience.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Comprehension implies that the viewer should be able to easily understand the information that is presented to them.
[src:chartjs/infographic] And finally, "retention" means that the viewer should remember the data presented by the infographic.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The order of importance of these provisions depends on the purpose of the infographic.
[src:chartjs/infographic] If the infographic is meant to convey information in an unbiased way, such as in the domains of academia or science, comprehension should be considered first, then retention, and finally, appeal.
[src:chartjs/infographic] However, if the infographic is being used for commercial purposes, then appeal becomes most important, followed by retention and comprehension.
[src:chartjs/infographic] When infographics are being used for editorial purposes, such as in a newspaper, the appeal is again most important but is followed first by comprehension and then retention.
[src:chartjs/infographic] However, the appeal and the retention can in practice be put together with the aid of a comprehensible layout design.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Recently, as an attempt to study the effect of the layout of an infographic on the comprehension of the viewers, a new Neural Network-based cognitive load estimation method was applied on different types of common layouts for the infographic design.
[src:chartjs/infographic] When the varieties of factors listed above are taken into consideration when designing infographics, they can be a highly efficient and effective way to convey large amounts of information in a visual manner.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Data visualizations are often used in infographics and may make up the entire infographic.
[src:chartjs/infographic] There are many types of visualizations that can be used to represent the same set of data.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Therefore, it is crucial to identify the appropriate visualization for the data set and infographic by taking into consideration graphical features such as position, size, shape, and color.
[src:chartjs/infographic] There are primarily five types of visualization categories – time-series data, statistical distributions, maps, hierarchies, and networking.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Time-series data is one of the most common forms of data visualization.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Examples of graphics in this category include index charts, stacked graphs, small multiples, and horizon graphs.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Index charts are ideal to use when raw values are less important than relative changes.
[src:chartjs/infographic] It is an interactive line chart that shows percentage changes for a collection of time-series data based on a selected index point.
[src:chartjs/infographic] For example, stock investors could use this because they are less concerned with the specific price and more concerned with the rate of growth.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Stacked graphs are area charts that are stacked on top of each other, and depict aggregate patterns.
[src:chartjs/infographic] They allow viewers to see overall patterns and individual patterns.
[src:chartjs/infographic] However, they do not support negative numbers and make it difficult to accurately interpret trends.
[src:chartjs/infographic] An alternative to stacked graphs is small multiples.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Instead of stacking each area chart, each series is individually shown so the overall trends of each sector are more easily interpreted.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Horizon graphs are a space efficient method to increase the data density of a time-series while preserving resolution.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Statistical distributions reveal trends based on how numbers are distributed.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Common examples include histograms and box-and-whisker plots, which convey statistical features such as mean, median, and outliers.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In addition to these common infographics, alternatives include stem-and-leaf plots, Q–Q plots, scatter plot matrices (SPLOM) and parallel coordinates.
[src:chartjs/infographic] For assessing a collection of numbers and focusing on frequency distribution, stem-and-leaf plots can be helpful.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The numbers are binned based on the first significant digit, and within each stack binned again based on the second significant digit.
[src:chartjs/infographic] On the other hand, Q–Q plots compare two probability distributions by graphing quantiles against each other.
[src:chartjs/infographic] This allows the viewer to see if the plot values are similar and if the two are linearly related.
[src:chartjs/infographic] SPLOM is a technique that represents the relationships among multiple variables.
[src:chartjs/infographic] It uses multiple scatter plots to represent a pairwise relation among variables.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Another statistical distribution approach to visualize multivariate data is parallel coordinates.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Rather than graphing every pair of variables in two dimensions, the data is repeatedly plotted on a parallel axis, and corresponding points are then connected with a line.
[src:chartjs/infographic] The advantage of parallel coordinates is that they are relatively compact, allowing many variables to be shown simultaneously.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Maps are a natural way to represent geographical data.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Time and space can be depicted through the use of flow maps.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Line strokes are used with various widths and colors to help encode information.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Choropleth maps, which encode data through color and geographical region, are also commonly used.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Graduated symbol maps are another method to represent geographical data.
[src:chartjs/infographic] They are an alternative to choropleth map and use symbols, such as pie charts for each area, over a map.
[src:chartjs/infographic] This map allows for more dimensions to be represented using various shapes, sizes, and colors.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Cartograms, on the other hand, completely distort the shape of a region and directly encode a data variable.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Instead of using a geographic map, regions are redrawn proportionally to the data.
[src:chartjs/infographic] For example, each region can be represented by a circle and the size/color is directly proportional to other information, such as population size.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Many data sets, such as spatial entities of countries or common structures for governments, can be organized into natural hierarchies.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Node-link diagrams, adjacency diagrams, and enclosure diagrams are all types of infographics that effectively communicate hierarchical data.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Node-link diagrams are a popular method due to the tidy and space-efficient results.
[src:chartjs/infographic] A node-link diagram is similar to a tree, where each node branches off into multiple sub-sections.
[src:chartjs/infographic] An alternative is adjacency diagrams, which is a space-filling variant of the node-link diagram.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Instead of drawing a link between hierarchies, nodes are drawn as solid areas with sub-sections inside of each section.
[src:chartjs/infographic] This method allows for size to be easily represented than in the node-link diagrams.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Enclosure diagrams are also a space-filling visualization method.
[src:chartjs/infographic] However, they use containment rather than adjacency to represent the hierarchy.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Similar to the adjacency diagram, the size of the node is easily represented in this model.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Network visualization explores relationships, such as friendships and cliques.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Three common types are force-directed layout, arc diagrams, and matrix view.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Force-directed layouts are a common and intuitive approach to network layout.
[src:chartjs/infographic] In this system, nodes are similar to charged particles, which repel each other.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Links are used to pull related nodes together.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Arc diagrams are one-dimensional layouts of nodes with circular arcs linking each node.
[src:chartjs/infographic] When used properly, with good order in nodes, cliques and bridges are easily identified in this layout.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Alternatively, mathematicians and computer scientists more often use matrix views.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Each value has an (x,y) value in the matrix that corresponds to a node.
[src:chartjs/infographic] By using color and saturation instead of text, values associated with the links can be perceived rapidly.
[src:chartjs/infographic] While this method makes it hard to view the path of the nodes, there are no line crossings, which in a large and highly connected network can quickly become too cluttered.
[src:chartjs/infographic] While all of these visualizations can be effectively used on their own, many modern infographics combine multiple types into one graphic, along with other features, such as illustrations and text.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Some modern infographics do not even contain data visualization, and instead are simply a colorful and succinct ways to present knowledge.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Fifty-three percent of the 30 most-viewed infographics on the infographic sharing site visual.ly did not contain actual data.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Comparison infographics are a type of visual representation that focuses on comparing and contrasting different elements, such as products, services, options, or features.
[src:chartjs/infographic] These infographics are designed to help viewers make informed decisions by presenting information in a clear and concise manner.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Comparison infographics can be highly effective in simplifying complex data and highlighting key differences between multiple items.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Infographics can be created by hand using simple everyday tools such as graph paper, pencils, markers, and rulers.
[src:chartjs/infographic] However, today they are more often created using computer software, which is often both faster and easier.
[src:chartjs/infographic] They can be created with general illustration software.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Diagrams can be manually created and drawn using software, which can be downloaded for the desktop or used online.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Templates can be used to get users started on their diagrams.
[src:chartjs/infographic] Additionally, the software allows users to collaborate on diagrams in real time over the Internet.
[src:chartjs/infographic] There are also numerous tools to create very specific types of visualizations, such as creating a visualization based on embedded data in the photos on a user's smartphone.
